[Event "Hanging Pawns (chapter 2 of Chess Structures A Grandmaster Guide): Mecking-Mareco (Campinas 2011)"]
[Date "2021.08.23"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/kev110195"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E53"]
[Opening "Nimzo-Indian Defense: Normal Variation, Gligoric System"]
[StudyName "pawn structures"]
[ChapterName "hanging"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/lZgjCMbW/0zBo00w6"]

{ This game illustrates the powerful d4-d5 break and the strong attack White obtains from it. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O cxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 b6 10. Qb3 Bxc3 11. bxc3 { We have reached the position of interest. This is a nice version of the hanging pawns for White as he has the bishop pair in an open position. } 11... Bb7 12. Ba3 Re8 13. Bb5 Bc6 14. Be2 { A typical manoeuvre. White wants to play Bc4-e2 to push c3-c4. By playing Bc4-b5 first, White causes Black's bishop to become misplaced on c6, where it will be vulnerable. Sooner of later, Black will have to waste a tempo with Bc6-b7. } 14... Nbd7 15. c4 { [%csl Gc2,Gd5] } 15... Qc7 16. Rfe1 { [%cal Ge1e7] } 16... Rad8 { The break 16...e5?! hoping to weaken the hanging pawns does not work well because White is ready to push d4-d5; his pieces are very active and the c4-pawn is a difficult target } (16... e5?! 17. d5 Bb7 18. h3 Nc5 19. Qe3 { White has a pleasant position and the game could continue : } 19... Nfe4 (19... Nfd7 20. Rad1 Rac8 21. Nh4 g6 22. Bg4! $16 { With strong pressure. } 22... f5? 23. Bxf5! gxf5 24. Nxf5 { With a deadly attack. }) 20. Nd2 Nxd2 21. Qxd2 Qd6 22. Bd1 Rac8 23. Re3 Re7 24. Bc2 f6 25. Rae1 $16 { White can continue to progress with h4-h5 and Rg3. }) 17. Bb2 { [%csl Gd8,Gb2][%cal Gd8d1] } 17... Nf8?! { There is no reason to give away the centre so easily. Better was : } (17... Ng4 { Provoking White to weaken his long diagonal with g2-g3. } 18. d5?! { White is not ready for this break due to : } (18. g3 Ngf6 19. Qe3 $14) (18. h3 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Qh2+ 20. Kf1 Ngf6 { When chances are approximately balanced. }) 18... Bb7 19. h3 Ngf6 20. dxe6 Rxe6 $10) 18. Ne5 { [%cal Re2d3,Rd3h7,Ga1d1,Gd1d8] } 18... Ba8 19. Bf1 Ng6 20. f3 { Preventing ...Nxe5 followed ...Ne4 or ...Ng4. Another option is : } (20. a4!? Nxe5 21. Rxe5 (21. dxe5? Ne4! $15 { Controlling key central squares such as c5. }) 21... Ng4 22. Rh5 Nf6 23. Rh4 $14 { With interesting attacking chances on the kingside. }) (20. Bd3 Nh4 21. Re3 (21. Bf1 Ng6 22. Re3 Ne4 23. Nxg6 hxg6 24. Rd1)) 20... Nh4 (20... Nxe5 21. Rxe5 h6 22. a4 $14 { White is better due to his space, the bishop pair and Black's lack of active plans. }) 21. Bd3?! { It was more important to activate the rook with the accurate 21.Rad1! preparing a d4-d5 break against Black's potential ...Nh5. } (21. Rad1 h6 (21... Nd7 22. Ng4 $14 { With attacking chances on the kingside. }) (21... Nh5?! 22. d5! $16) 22. Qe3 $14 { With a good and flexible position. }) 21... Nd7 (21... Nh5! { It would allow Black to gain counterplay on the kingside. } 22. Rad1? (22. Bf1 f6 23. Ng4 Nf4 { Therefore, it is necessary to give up the bishop pair with : }) (22. Be4 Nf4 23. Bxa8 Rxa8 24. g3 Nh3+ 25. Kf1 f6!? $13) 22... f6! { And now, Black wins material with : } 23. Ng4 Nf4 24. Bf1 Nh3+! 25. Kh1 h5! 26. Ne3 Nf2+ 27. Kg1 Nxd1 $19) 22. Nxd7 Rxd7?! { This move is a mistake as Black is no longer able to prevent the d4-d5 break. More stubborn was : } (22... Qxd7 23. Qc2 h6 24. Qf2 Nf5 25. Bxf5 exf5 26. d5 f6 27. Qd4 $14 { White enjoys a central passed pawn. }) 23. Qc2 Kh8 { The optimistic 23...Bxf3?! fails due to :
Safer was : 23...Ng6 } (23... Bxf3?! 24. Qf2 (24. Bxh7+!) 24... Nxg2 25. Qxf3 Nxe1 26. Rxe1 $16 { When two bishops are far stronger than a rook and two pawns in this open game. }) (23... Ng6 24. d5 Red8 25. Qc3 f6! (25... e5? 26. Bf5 (26. Bxg6!? { Winning a pawn. }) 26... Re7 27. a4 { Preventing ...b6-b5 } 27... Nh4 28. Be4 Ree8 29. Rac1 { It gives White a dominating position. }) 26. Bxg6 hxg6 27. Rxe6 b5 28. cxb5 Bxd5 29. Qxc7 Rxc7 30. Re2 $14 { Black has drawing chances due to the opposite-colored bishops. }) 24. Qf2 { An interesting option was : 24.d5! immediately developing an attack } (24. d5!) (24. Bxh7? f5! { And the bishop is lost. }) 24... Qd8 (24... Ng6 25. a4 $16 { White can prepare and threaten with either break, a4-a5 or d4-d5. }) 25. d5! { This well-prepared break is simply winning for White. Black cannot defend against such a strong initiative, especially since his pieces lack coordination and White possesses the bishop pair. } 25... b5 (25... exd5? 26. Qxh4! Qxh4?? (26... Rxe1+ 27. Rxe1 Qxh4 28. Re8#) 27. Rxe8#) 26. Bc2 Rg8 { More stubborn was : 26...bxc4 though after : } (26... bxc4 27. Ba4 Nf5 (27... Bxd5? 28. Bxd7 Qxd7 29. Qxh4 $18) 28. Bxd7 Qxd7 29. dxe6 fxe6 30. Be5 { Black is technically lost. }) 27. dxe6 fxe6 (27... Rd2 28. Re2 Rxe2 29. Qxe2 fxe6 30. cxb5 { And White wins. }) 28. Rad1! $18 { A simple yet beautiful move which illustrates White's overwhelming initiative once d4-d5 is achieved.. Black has no hope of dealing with the multiple threats, the most direct being Rxd7 followed by Qxh4. } (28. Rxe6? Rd2! 29. Re2 Rxe2 30. Qxe2 Qg5 { Threatening ...Bxf3. } 31. Rf1 bxc4 $16 { When Black is holding the game for longer. }) 28... Rxd1 29. Rxd1 Qg5 30. Qg3! { Nice move! It forces Black to choose between a lost endgame and allowing a mating attack. } 30... Qe7 (30... Qxg3 31. hxg3 Ng6 32. cxb5 { Winning due to the bishop pair, the initiative and the extra pawn. }) 31. Rd7! { Black resigned in view of 31...Qxd7 32.Qxh4 and there is no satisfactory way to prevent Qxh7#.
It was not possible for Black just to break the hanging pawns with 14...e5. White's good piece placement rendered this move ineffective.
White's bishop pair played a central role in many positions. They are very helpful in an open position such as with hanging pawns. Black seemingly underestimated the decisive d4-d5 break. It was necessary to prevent it, though passive defense would have been unpleasant as well. } *


